Telephone Ashland 7435\nl 500 FIFTH AVE. felephone Vanderbilt 8354\nBERLIN 4s\nHAMBURG 4y2.\nMUNICH 4s\nFRANKFORT 4.\nDRESDEN 4'/2s\nAll Foreign Bonds\nDUNHAMftfo\nSPECIALISTS\n4J Exchange Piace, New York.\nr*lm*h*m*e Hanover\n4MmSc\n**TAJmU9M*a mo*\nPJuma Orofcti. 8B\nBell Wether of the leather\nstocks?after a spectacular\nmarket career now settling\ndown a discussion oi\npresent and future status\nof the common and pre?\nferred?also an article on\nThe Leather Industry?\nOther features\nin\nAak MARKET\nw?B\" OPINION\nR. H. MacMASTERS CO.\nMember a ConaolidataS Stoofe Each.. QfN.Y.\n82-94 Broad St. New York\ntVhtmai Abroad CM?. mtira sTirai Flaen\nCSsittagex MUtrau'SM 3SJa*nm<?i<1 Htye tXaavsx\n\nAsks Receiver for Maxweil\nWILMINGTON, Dei., Feb. 15.?\nCharles J. True, of Illinois, haa filed a\nbill in the Federal District Court ask?\ning for an injunction and appointment\nof a receiver for the Maxweil Mctor\nCompany, a Delaware corporation, with\nbusiness establishments in Ohio, Mich?\nigan ar.d Illinois.\nInvestment Information\nQueatione of general interest to in\nvestora will be answered in thic eel\numn, in which c.aee orly initials will\nhe used. Otkers will be answered by\ntnail. Addreeg all inquiries, incloe\ning a stamped, addressed envelope, t*\nFinancial Editor, The Tribune, 264\nNassau Street, New York City.\nThe Market\nWhile the large volume of financing\nthat/ has been done in the last few\nweeks has strengthened the balance\nsheet position and has tided over the\ncurrent banking necessities of many\ncompanies, it has not answered the\nquestion whether there is any imme?\ndiate prospect of a lower rato for\nmoney. It is the opinion of some bank?\ners that tho peak of interest charges\nhas been reached, at Ieast for the\nstrongest companies, but there will be\nonly very slightly lower rates for\nmoney for industrial and railroad de?\nvelopment until income taxes are re?\nduced. It is not inaccurate to say that\na 7 to 8 per cent interest rate carried\nby the security of a strong company\ndoes not so much reflcct the nrice of\nmoney as it does the price of money\nwith the income tax deduction. When,\nand only when, these securities sell\nex income tax deduction, it is argued\nthat we may hope to got 5 per cent\nmoney for industrial needs.\nExchanging Frisco Bonds\nQuestion?I have two bonds ol' the St.\nT>ouls San Franclsco itallroad Company,\nfirst mortgage 6 per cent Southwestorn\nDivision, duo 1947, and am ln doubt\nwhether to exchange same for bondn under\nthe reorganizatton.?O. W.\nAnswer?If yon exchange your two\nbor.ds of the old company, the St.\nLouis San Francisco Railroad, for\nbonds of the new company, the St.\nLouis San Francisco Railway Co.,\nyou will receive two $1,000 and one\n$500 St. Louis San Francisco Railway\nCo. prior lien mortgage gold series A\n4 per cent bonds and in addition $125\ncash. You will get the same annual\nincome from the new bonds an the old,\nnarnely $100. The $125 cash will be\nin the nature of compensation for\nmaking the exchange. Recently the\nbonds sold at 77 for old 5s and 62 for\nthe new 4s. At these prices you would\nexchange securities with a market\nvalue of $1640 for cash and securities\ntotaling $1,675. While there is pos?\nsibly a theoretical greater security\nin the mortgage securing the old 5s,\nthe fact that of the $1,500,000 total of\nold 5s more than $1,005,000 have been\nexchanged or rcdeemed would indi\ncate that most of the holders of the\nold bonds thought the exchange advan\ntageous, and so it appears to us.\nWill Buy Seasoned Stocks\nQuestion?I own some of tha following\nbonds. Wlll you please advlse me lf they\nare all -.veil secured and safe as to prin?\ncipal and de3irab!e to hold as long term\ninvestments? International Mercantile Ma?\nrine 6d, Detroit Edison Company refunding\n5s, Chicago, Milwaukee St. Paul con?\nvertible iMs. I now wish to purchase\nKome seasoned preferred stocks and shall\nchoose those issues which I have seen you\nrecommend so often in your Investment\ncolumn., vlz.: United States Steel pre?\nferred, Standard Oil of New Jersey pre?\nferred and American Bank NoU pre?\nferred?J. C.\nAnswer-?Your Detroit Edison re?\nfunding 5s and Marine 6s are goo*d\nbusiness men's investments, in our\nopinion, especially the Edisons. The\n.\"?'t. Paul 4Via are somewhat speculative\non account of the recent difficulties of\nthe road and the elements of uncer?\ntainty in the general outlook. The\npreferred stocks you mention are high\ngrade.\nBuying Stocks in Theater Lobbies\nQuestion?I would like little Informa?\ntion concerning a. small Investment I made\nfor my littlo son. Some months ago\nLoew'p, Inc, put up for saie ln the!:\ntheaters shares of their stock to be sold\nat |21 per share. I purchased two of\nthem, paying for them at $8 down and }G\nper month. A few days after I discovered\nthn day I bought they were only 17 and\na fraction on Wall Street. Some one told\nme after I had paid for one I could de?\ncline to buy. the other and demand my\ncertificate for the one paid for. I would\nlike you to advlse me if that ls right, as I\nwrite them to that effect and they wroto\nme back to say I would havo to pay for\nit or otherwlse allow them to Befl them\nand aftor deductlng their commission uend\nme the balance if any. I understand a\nbroker gets $1 I'or selling stocka of any\namount, ls tliflt. correct? And do you\nthink it Inwful for tliern to chargo tnar\nprlco when they could be houirht muoh\noheaper? Another qusstlon l wouUl like\nto natl. ts tho Motion Plcturo ProdMcIng\nCotrtpany any good?.Mrs. IT. r.\nAnswer?You know now thaf Loew's,\nInc, stock is too speculative for thc\n3nve8tment of money for your littlo\nson. We cannot tell what you can de?\nmand i'rom your brokor, becauae w,e do\nnot know the terms of tho *agrcement\nyou made with him. Nor do we know\nwhether you were correctly informed\nabout the price. Some brokers charge\n?*1 and some art much as Jji'J.oO as\nminimum comrnission on any one lot\nof stock. The transaction was prob?\nably legal. Your only protection in a\ncase like thin is to be sure before you\nbuy that your broker is trustworthy.\nThe other moving picture stock is also\ntoo speculative for you. We suggest\nthat you buy Liberty bonds Orst, and i\nthen investment bonds or good pre- I\nferred stocks. You will be free from i\nworry and your principal will be safe.\nGo to the theater to be amused and j\nbuy your stocks in tho stock market.\nAgricultural Chemical's New Issue\nQuestion?Kindly give mo what Infor?\nmation you can as to how good an Invest?\nment you think American Agricultural\nChemieal llrst refunding murtsraeo bonda.-?\nP. M. H.\nAnswer American Agricultural\nChemieal first and refunding 7% per\ncent bonds are secured by a mortgage\non the company's property, subject only\nto $6,959,000 outstanding convertible 6\nper cent bonds, due 1928, for the re\ntirement of which refunding bonds are\nreserved. The business outlook for the\ncompany is good, and, in our opinion,\nthe bonds are an attractive investment\nfor a business man. They yield 1\\\nper cent.\nStocks Not Proper for a Widow\nQuestion?I ask th* followiner Informa?\ntion for an old wldowed lady nnd several\n(.cqualntancfs. Ia the Crunader Fllma Cor?\nporation a good rnvestment, and are the\nmon behind it hone.nt and ri.li.iblp? What\ndo you think ol' tho Remlnrrton Phono\nfcruph Company aa ar. investment, also the\nman at tho head of the orsranlzatio-n?\nV. A. A.\nAnswer?In our opio\"n the motion\npicture stocks* which you mention\nare much too .speculative for a\nwidow dependent on income. She will\nbe better otT to confine her investments\nto good preferred stocks and bonds.\nPossession of common stocks involves\na business risk which she probably\ncannot afford to carry. The Remington\nPhonograph stock will remain highly\nspeculative until the company shows\nthat it can manufacture and market in?\nstruments at a profit.\nWoman Worries Abont A. P. Tea\nQuestion?Three or four monthrj ago my\nhusband >ought six preferred shares in\nthe Oreal Atlantic and Paclflo Tea Com?\npany at $100 a share, and since then I\nhave worrled about it for fear lt may not\nbe Just safe, and aa we are poor, and try?\ning to buy a house, one cannot afford to\nlose that much money. Ho I am writing\nto you to see what you think of it, or if\nyou can tell me whether lt ls safe??\nMra. W. K.\nAnswer?Dividends on the prefewed\natock of tho Great Atlantic and Pacific\nTea Company, Inc, have been regularly\npaid Eince incorporation, in 1916. We\nhave no late statement of earnings\nThe company floated an $18,000,000\nborfd issue in June, 1919. We do not\nthink you are threatened with loss on\nyour investment, but people in your\nposition should choose Btocks which\nare more seasoned, in our oninion.\n\nFour full columns of in?\nvestment questions and an?\nswer* are published in The\nTribune every Sunday.\nPhiladelphia\nB*,f,1.,,. Open-Hl*fl?. \"Oow. L?rrt.\n*l AlllancA Ins... ia is ij i?\n265 Am Stores 63 65 Bi sl\n93 Buffalo Kusq.. 73 ?8 7\" 7*\n5li ^o P' 43 43 a% ii\nlaCambrla Iron. 27 37 ?7 ?7\n-45 Elec Storage..10S loiu ia? int\n300 Qen Asphalt... 69 89 SI\n*3 0 Lehigh N'av.. 66 66 f*? ee\n200 Ph Co cumpf ?3 32 81U u\n1092 Phila Elec. 22% 22% Sj#\n85 do pf 23 28 27% 2?5t\nPhll lna Wlre 61% 51% 61% liu,\n2\\*-lhn \\ractlon. 65** 56 *J tjjg 65%\n26 Tono Belmont 1% i j J?\nrr 2i ??a Imp* Z4** 3**H 34%\n55 do pf 49% 49fi 49|*?\nswni?.n Tr'\"\"-* 301.^ 30% 3034 30%\n3 Westmor Coal 80 80 80 gt)\nS'OOO Ii V gf-'l is, 2003OI7S*i 7*8% 7SW 711'\n1000 Phll Co cons 6s 76% 78'4 ii& ll)l\nJOOOPh Blee lst Ga 83*g 83% 83% ?a&\n1000 L V Coal Bs. 94% 04U 11 it 22C\nMiscellaneous Markets\nPublic Utility Secnritlea\nSecurity. Bid.\nC P R L 13\ndo pf... 33\nBi BfrS pf 81\nE D K pf. CO\nEG&F lc6 94\ndo 6%cn 85\ndo 83>pf 85\ndo 8%cn\nF L T. 6\ndo pref. 42\na ft El 3.200\ndo pref. 75\nNor St Pr 44\ndo pref. 78\nRep RyL 6*A\ndo pref. IS\nSo Cal Ed 89\n?do pref. 99\nSt G E 12\ndo pr